<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How many plants can I fit in a 4x8 raised bed?", answer: "It depends on the spacing. At 12 inch spacing square-pattern, a 4 × 8 bed holds 5 × 9 = 45 plants. At 6 inch spacing, it holds 9 × 17 = 153. At 18 inch spacing, 3 × 6 = 18. Triangular spacing fits about 15 percent more plants into the same bed by offsetting each row. Square Foot Gardening uses 1-per-square for cabbage and broccoli, 4-per-square for lettuce, 9-per-square for bush beans and spinach, and 16-per-square for carrots, radishes, and onions." },
  { question: "What is triangular vs square plant spacing?", answer: "Square spacing arranges plants on a grid where every plant is the same distance from its neighbors in both directions. Triangular (staggered) spacing offsets each row by half the plant spacing, so each plant has 6 equidistant neighbors forming a hexagonal pattern. Triangular packs 15 percent more plants into the same area and is slightly more efficient, but square is easier to plant, weed, and harvest." },
  { question: "How far apart should tomato plants be?", answer: "Indeterminate tomatoes need 24 to 36 inches between plants. Determinate (bush) tomatoes can go at 18 to 24 inches. In a staked or caged setup, tighter is fine — 18 inch stakes with 18 inches between plants. In a sprawling ground culture, spread them 36 to 48 inches. Close spacing increases airflow problems and encourages fungal disease, so err on the side of more space if you have room." },
  { question: "Does closer spacing give more yield?", answer: "Up to a point. Double-cropping and intensive spacing increase yield per square foot but not per plant. Beyond the optimum, plants shade each other, compete for water and nutrients, and yield drops. For example, carrots at 2 inch spacing give lots of small carrots; at 4 inches they give larger, more uniform roots but about half the count. Most vegetables have a sweet spot where total yield per area is maximized — usually close to the recommended row-spacing for traditional rows." },
  { question: "How many plants per square foot?", answer: "The Square Foot Gardening rule: 1 large plant, 4 medium, 9 small, or 16 tiny per square foot. Examples — 1: cabbage, broccoli, pepper; 4: lettuce, swiss chard, parsley; 9: bush beans, spinach, beets; 16: carrots, radishes, onions. This rule works best in intensively gardened beds with rich soil because close plantings demand lots of nutrients." }
]) %>

